# Unit Testing Principles, Practices, and Patterns (Vladimir Khorikov) - Integration Focus

Although title says "Unit", 50% of book is about how integration tests really save the project.

- **Refactoring Resistance**: Integration test shouldn't break if you change internal function name.
- **Regression Protection**: Test should fail if business logic alters.
- **Fast Feedback**: Optimize Atlassian API mocks so test flies.
- **Maintainability**: Avoid code duplication in test setups.
- **Use "Humble Object Pattern"**: Extract hard-to-test logic from Forge UI components.
- **Don't test constants**: Don't verify a string is a string.
- **Integration Test vs End-to-End**: In Forge, integration test is your E2E (since you don't control Jira).
- **Use "Mockist" vs "Classic" Testing**: Prefer "Classic" style (using real objects) for integration.
- **Identify external dependencies**: Classify which you can control and which you can't.
- **Test "Database Schema"**: Ensure data in Storage remains compatible.
- **Avoid "Fragile Tests"**: Those failing due to irrelevant UI Kit changes.
- **Use "Parameterize Tests"**: Test multiple Jira states with same logic.
- **Verify final state**: Test ends checking what remained in Storage.
- **Don't test third-party logic**: Don't test lodash works, test YOUR usage of it.
- **Isolate CI Environment**: Use environment variables for Forge development environments.
- **Use "Test Double" with precision.**
- **Test state transitions.**
- **Avoid spaghetti code in test files.**
- **Use "Setup Decorators" to prepare Confluence context.**
- **Prioritize quality over quantity.**
